d communal values and an active citizenry-to justify their goals.Kalman, a historian and a lawyer, suggests that reliance on history in legal thinking makes sense at a time when the Supreme Court repeatedly declares that it will protect only those liberties rooted in history and tradition. There are pitfalls in interdisciplinary argumentation, she cautions, for historians' reactions to this use of their work have been unenthusiastic and even hostile. Yet lawyers, law professors, and historians have cooperated in some recent Supreme Court cases, and Kalman concludes with a practical examination of the ways they can work together more effectively as social activists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aConstitutional lawxPhilosophyxUnited States. 0aConstitutional lawxUnited States. 0aConstitutional lawzUnited StatesxPhilosophy. 0aConstitutional lawzUnited States. 0aLawxMethodologyxHistoryxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aLawzUnited StatesxMethodologyxHistory. 0aLiberalismxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aLiberalismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300147308423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300147308.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles